# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: telecom-5g
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The 3GPP specification 38 series provides the technical details behind 5G NR, the successor of LTE.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The study of 5G NR within 3GPP started in 2015, and the first specification was made available by the end of 2017.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] While the 3GPP standardization process was ongoing, the industry had already begun efforts to implement infrastructure compliant with the draft standard, with the first large-scale commercial launch of 5G NR having occurred in the end of 2018.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Since 2019, many operators have deployed 5G NR networks and handset manufacturers have developed 5G NR enabled handsets.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] A "Non-Standalone" (NSA) gNodeB is built on an existing LTE (4G) base station (eNodeB or eNB).
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Ooredoo was the first carrier to launch a commercial 5G NR network, in May 2018 in Qatar.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Other carriers around the world have been following suit.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] In 2018, 3GPP published Release 15, which includes what is described as "Phase 1" standardization for 5G NR.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The timeline for Release 16, which will be "5G phase 2", follows a freeze date of March 2020 and a completion date of June 2020, Release 17 was originally scheduled for delivery in September 2021. but, because of the COVID-19 pandemic, it was rescheduled for June 2022.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Rel.18 is referred to as "NR Advanced" signifying another milestone in wireless communication systems.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] NR Advanced will include features such as eXtended Reality (XR), AI/ML studies, and Mobility enhancements.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Mobility is in the core of 3GPP technology and has so far been handled on Layer 3 (RRC), now, in Rel-18 the work on mobility is to introduce lower layer triggered mobility.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Initial 5G NR launches will depend on existing LTE infrastructure in non-standalone (NSA) mode, before maturation of the standalone (SA) mode with the 5G core network.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Additionally, the spectrum can be dynamically shared between LTE and 5G NR.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] To make better use of existing assets, carriers may opt to dynamically share it between LTE and 5G NR.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The spectrum is multiplexed over time between both generations of mobile networks depending on user demand, while still using the LTE network for control functions.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Dynamic spectrum sharing (DSS) may be deployed on existing LTE equipment as long as it is compatible with 5G NR.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Only the 5G NR terminal needs to be compatible with DSS.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The non-standalone (NSA) mode of 5G NR refers to an option of 5G NR deployment that depends on the control plane of an existing LTE network for control functions, while 5G NR is exclusively focused on the user plane.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] This is reported to speed up 5G adoption, however some operators and vendors have criticized prioritizing the introduction of 5G NR NSA on the grounds that it could hinder the implementation of the standalone mode of the network.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] It uses the same core network as a 4G network, but with upgraded radio equipment.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The standalone (SA) mode of 5G NR refers to using 5G cells for both signalling and information transfer, essentially a 5G network without any legacy 4G infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] It includes the new 5G Packet Core architecture instead of relying on the 4G Evolved Packet Core, to allow the deployment of 5G without the LTE network.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] It is expected to have lower cost, better efficiency, and to assist development of new use cases.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] However, initial deployment might see slower speed than existing network due to the allocation of spectrum.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] It uses a new core network dedicated to 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] The length of the cyclic prefix is inversely proportional to the subcarrier spacing.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] It is 4.7 μs with 15 kHz, and 4.7 / 16 = 0.29 μs for 240 kHz subcarrier spacing.
[src:telecom-5g/5g-nr] Additionally, higher subcarrier spacings allow for reduced latency and increased support for high-frequency bands, essential for the ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) and enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) applications in 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Like earlier cellular systems, 5G networks divide service areas into smaller zones called cells, which are served by fixed cell sites.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Compatible devices connect by radio to local base stations, which are linked to an operator's core network and to external networks such as the Internet through backhaul connections.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G can be deployed using low-band, mid-band, and high-band radio spectrum, with coverage and performance depending heavily on the frequencies used, network design, congestion, and device capabilities.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Compared with 4G, 5G is designed to provide higher data rates, greater network capacity, lower latency, improved support for dense device deployments, and more flexible network management.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Actual user speeds are typically much lower than peak values and vary by operator, location, spectrum band, signal quality, and network load.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G is used for mobile broadband, fixed wireless access, private and industrial networks, and machine-type communications.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Its standards support features such as network slicing, edge computing, non-public networks, and ultra-reliable low-latency services, although these capabilities are not present in every deployment.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The rollout of 5G has required new spectrum allocations and upgrades to radio access, transport, and core-network infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It has also raised issues involving deployment cost, energy use, vendor security, and public claims about radio-frequency health effects.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G is being deployed alongside 4G networks and is expected to coexist with them for many years.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2008, NASA and the Machine-to-Machine Intelligence Corporation (M2Mi) conducted nanosatellite communication studies that influenced early next-generation network concepts.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2012, New York University established NYU Wireless, a research center focused on millimeter-wave communication.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The same year, the University of Surrey founded the 5G Innovation Centre, funded by £35 million from public and industry partners including Huawei and Samsung.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Also in 2012, the European Union launched the *Mobile and Wireless Communications Enablers for the Twenty-Twenty Information Society (METIS)* project to align emerging network research with international standardization.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2013, the ITU-R Working Party 5D began studies on *IMT-2020*, later formalized as the 5G standard.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] During the same period, major firms such as Samsung Electronics, NTT Docomo, and Huawei conducted early trials.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Samsung tested a prototype achieving more than 1 Gbit/s across 2 km using 8 × 8 MIMO antennas.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] NTT Docomo received a government award at CEATEC for high-speed network development, while Huawei announced a US$600 million program to advance mobile network technology.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] On April 3, 2019, South Korea launched its national network, the first full commercial deployment.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Hours later, Verizon began limited service in select U.S. cities.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In June 2019, Globe Telecom introduced the Philippines' first next-generation network, and in December 2019, AT&T launched a consumer service in the United States that expanded nationwide during 2020.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Commercial 5G deployment expanded rapidly through 2020.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Beyond public mobile networks, it was also adopted in private industrial and enterprise systems, including operation in unlicensed spectrum (NR-U) and licensed non-public networks (NPNs).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Private 5G networks became important for Industry 4.0 automation and smart manufacturing.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Early rollouts used non-standalone (NSA) mode—with 4G cores—before networks transitioned to standalone (SA) mode with dedicated 5G cores.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] South Korea’s 2019 rollout used equipment from Samsung, Ericsson, and Nokia; LG U Plus also deployed Huawei hardware.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Samsung supplied most of the roughly 86,000 sites, while SK Telecom, KT Corporation, and LG U Plus concentrated coverage in major cities using the 3.5 GHz band under NSA operation.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Reported download speeds averaged 200–400 Mbit/s, and subscriptions grew from about 260,000 to 4.7 million during 2019.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Following these early deployments, T-Mobile US launched the first nationwide standalone network in 2020.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Ericsson projected that by the mid-2020s, 5G networks would reach about 65 percent of the global population.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Major suppliers of 5G radio and core systems included Altiostar, Cisco Systems, Datang Telecom/Fiberhome, Ericsson, Huawei, Nokia, Qualcomm, Samsung, and ZTE.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Huawei was estimated to hold about 70 percent of global 5G base stations by 2023.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] By 2022, network speeds in many regions had stabilized, and operators began testing 5.5G upgrades to improve capacity and latency.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] By the early 2020s, large-scale commercial 5G networks were active across most developed markets, and rollout in developing regions was still accelerating.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Small cells are low-power radio nodes that extend network capacity in dense or indoor areas.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] They operate over short distances, typically a few dozen to a few hundred metres, and are used to maintain coverage for mmWave signals.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Massive multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) systems use large antenna arrays to increase capacity and spectral efficiency.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] They extend conventional MIMO by serving multiple users simultaneously and steering signals toward them to reduce interference.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Beamforming directs radio energy toward specific users.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In analogue beamforming, antenna outputs are combined to focus signal power in one direction.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Digital beamforming transmits data streams across multiple layers to improve signal strength and reliability.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Non-orthogonal multiple access assigns different power levels to users sharing the same frequency resources to improve spectral efficiency.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G NR uses polar codes for control channels and low-density parity-check codes (LDPC) for data channels, replacing the turbo codes used in 4G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Research has explored the use of 5G mmWave networks for wireless power transfer.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Studies using wavelengths between 1 mm and 10 mm remain experimental.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The 5G core (5GC) is a service-oriented, software-defined system that separates control and user planes and supports flexible deployment.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It replaces the 4G Evolved Packet Core with modular, software-based network functions.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) enable software-based configuration, scaling, and management of networks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Together with network slicing, these technologies support applications such as the Internet of things, connected vehicles, and industrial automation.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Service-based architecture (SBA) integrates SDN and NFV principles and replaces the 4G EPC framework with modular network functions that communicate through RESTful APIs.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Each function registers with a network repository function (NRF), which enables independent scaling and interoperability.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Each network function performs a defined role within the 5G core, replacing or extending elements from the 4G EPC.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G networks use multiple parts of the radio spectrum.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] They operate across three main frequency ranges—low, mid, and high bands—which balance speed, coverage, and signal quality differently.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Between 2016 and 2019, regulators in many regions, including the United States and the European Union, reallocated large sections of spectrum for 5G through auctions and new licensing rules.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] By 2019, more than 50 countries had assigned or planned to assign 5G frequencies.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 3GPP Release 16, the standard added 5G NR-U, allowing operation in both unlicensed and licensed spectrum.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Low- and mid-band 5G provide broad coverage and reliable indoor reception.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] High-band signals weaken rapidly and may lose over 100 dB when passing through common building materials.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Operators use beamforming antennas, small cells, and signal repeaters to extend range and improve indoor coverage.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Technologies such as License Assisted Access (LAA) and LTE-WLAN Aggregation (LWA) let mobile networks share unlicensed spectrum with Wi-Fi.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Cloud-based RAN systems and dense small-cell layouts help narrow the performance gap between cellular and Wi-Fi links.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The ITU-R defines three main application areas for 5G: enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB), ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), and massive machine-type communications (mMTC).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] These categories describe the main uses of 5G: faster mobile connections (eMBB), highly reliable and responsive communication (URLLC), and large-scale links between machines (mMTC).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] By 2020, eMBB was widely deployed, while URLLC and mMTC were still in development.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) provides much faster internet and higher capacity than 4G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It supports intensive data use in busy areas such as city centres, stadiums, and transport hubs.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) are designed for time-critical applications such as factory automation, remote medical procedures, and traffic systems.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Shorter transmission delays improve precision and reliability.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Massive machine-type communications (mMTC) connect large numbers of low-power devices such as sensors and meters.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] These networks underpin the Internet of things (IoT) by allowing machines to exchange data autonomously in industry, transport, and urban systems.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G is used in transport, manufacturing, and energy systems that require constant, low-latency communication.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The 5G Automotive Association develops vehicle-to-everything (C-V2X) standards that allow cars to exchange safety information with nearby vehicles and infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Drones and autonomous vehicles use 5G for navigation, remote control, and real-time data transmission.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Low-latency connections also enable digital twin models—virtual copies of machines or buildings that show real-time performance data used for monitoring and maintenance.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G extends to public safety, broadband access, and media delivery.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Emergency services use it for live video, data, and reliable push-to-talk communication.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Fixed wireless access (FWA) provides home and business broadband using 5G radio links instead of wired connections, especially in rural areas where laying cables is costly.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G Broadcast trials in Europe show that local 5G networks can deliver live television and radio to many devices simultaneously without using mobile data plans.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Voice over NR (VoNR) allows phone calls to be made over 5G's internet-based network, similar to Voice over LTE (VoLTE) on 4G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G can deliver much higher data rates than 4G, up to ten times faster.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Theoretical peak download speeds reach up to 20 Gbit/s.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In practice, average 5G download speeds in the United States have been measured at about 186 Mbit/s by T-Mobile, while South Korea in 2022 led globally with averages near 430 Mbit/s.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G networks are also designed to provide much greater total capacity and efficiency than 4G, with up to a hundredfold projected increase.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The most widely deployed version, sub-6 GHz (mid-band) 5G, provides speeds of roughly 10–1000 Mbit/s with wider reach than mmWave bands.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] C-Band (n77/n78) was introduced in the U.S. in 2022, though activation by Verizon and AT&T was briefly delayed due to FAA safety concerns.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The highest 5G speed measured in a deployed network is 5.9 Gbit/s (2023).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Low-band frequencies such as n5 cover larger areas per cell but deliver lower data rates of around 5–250 Mbit/s.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Typical *air latency* for 5G is around 8–12 ms, excluding retransmissions and handovers.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Verizon reported about 30 ms latency in early deployments.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Edge servers located near base stations can reduce round-trip time to roughly 14 ms and minimize jitter to about 1.8 ms.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Latency increases substantially during handovers, ranging from 50 to 150 ms depending on network conditions.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Ongoing research focuses on reducing these interruptions by adjusting handover margins and time-to-trigger parameters.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G uses adaptive modulation and coding schemes (MCS) to maintain a low block error rate (BLER).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] When the error rate exceeds a threshold, the system automatically switches to a lower MCS to prioritize reliability over speed.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The range of 5G varies with transmit power, frequency, and interference.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] High-frequency mmWave bands (e.g., n258) have a shorter range than mid-band (n78), which in turn has a shorter range than low-band (n5).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Operators use network simulation and drive testing to measure the actual range and coverage of these bands, as real-world performance can differ from marketing claims.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The term 5G was first associated with the International Telecommunication Union's IMT-2020 standard.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It defines peak download and upload rates of 20 and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) later proposed its 5G New Radio (NR) technology for IMT-2020.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Early FR1 deployments reusing 4G infrastructure (non-standalone mode) have been reported to provide 15–50 percent higher throughput than advanced 4G networks under favorable conditions.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G networks can operate in Non-Standalone (NSA) mode using existing LTE infrastructure or Standalone (SA) mode using a dedicated 5G Core (5GC) network.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Other organizations also contribute to 5G standards.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The DECT-2020 specification defines DECT NR+, a non-cellular, mesh-based radio system recognized by ITU as part of 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The IEEE defines standards for wired links between the remote radio unit (RRU) and the baseband unit (BBU).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5Gi was developed in India by IIT Madras, IIT Hyderabad, the Telecommunications Standards Development Society India (TSDSI) and the Centre of Excellence in Wireless Technology (CEWiT).
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It extends 5G coverage in rural and remote areas through low-mobility large-cell (LMLC) configurations.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5Gi was merged in April 2022 into the global 5G NR standard in 3GPP Release 17.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In the Internet of things (IoT), 3GPP defines the evolution of NB-IoT and eMTC to support low-power wide-area applications such as connected sensors and meters.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 3GPP standards also define advanced communication services for voice and connected devices.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 3GPP defines Voice over NR as a technology that enables native, high-quality voice over a 5G Standalone network through the 5G System Architecture.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Unlike early 5G Non-Standalone deployments that relied on Evolved Packet System Fallback, VoNR integrates directly with the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) used in VoLTE.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It uses NAS protocols to establish high-priority QoS flows that support URLLC requirements for voice traffic.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Support for 5G Standalone is a prerequisite for VoNR.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] VoNR benefits from the enhanced security architecture of the 5G Core network, including improved subscriber identity protection.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] VoNR delivers superior audio quality through the Enhanced Voice Services (EVS) codec, which must adhere to rigorous terminal acoustic requirements and standardized testing procedures.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Most phones released since 2023 (such as the iPhone 15 series and newer flagship devices) support VoNR, but availability depends on carrier enablement in specific areas.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 3GPP also defines non-terrestrial networks (NTN) that use satellites and airborne platforms to provide coverage where ground networks are impractical.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G-Advanced, also known as 5.5G or 5G-A, is defined in 3GPP Release 18 as a transition between 5G and 6G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It adds features for more efficient spectrum use, lower energy demand, and higher reliability.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The release introduces AI- and ML-based network management, extended-reality services, and communication support for autonomous systems.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Release 18 specifies improved time-synchronization methods independent of the GNSS and built-in geolocation functions.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It extends non-terrestrial support to satellite and airborne communication.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G Reduced Capability (RedCap) in 3GPP Release 17 is designed to bridge the gap between high-performance 5G devices and low-power IoT technologies such as LTE-M and NB-IoT.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] It was created to address use cases between Enhanced Mobile Broadband (eMBB), Ultra-Reliable Low-Latency Communications (URLLC), and Massive Machine-Type Communication (mMTC) technologies.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA) compiled the first database of 5G-compatible products, listing 23 manufacturers and 33 models across categories such as smartphones, hotspots, and customer-premises equipment.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Later surveys recorded more than one hundred announced products from over fifty vendors.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Early 5G modem chipsets were released by Intel, MediaTek, Qualcomm, and Samsung, followed by additional platforms in subsequent product generations.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The Samsung Galaxy S10 5G was among the first smartphones to support 5G networks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Other early 5G models included the Nokia 8.3 5G, designed for operation across low- to mid-band frequencies; the Google Pixel 5 and Pixel 4a (5G); and Apple's iPhone 12 series, the company's first generation with 5G capability.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] By the early 2020s, most high-end smartphones featured 5G capability, while some consumer devices still lack full support.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] As a result, the practical benefits for mid range phone users have been modest, and 5G adoption has lagged behind expectations.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2019, the European Commission and the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) warned that 5G networks could expand potential attack surfaces for state actors, recommending diversification of suppliers.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Nokia and Ericsson are the only European manufacturers.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Researchers from ETH Zurich and partner universities found weaknesses in the 5G authentication process that could expose users to new security risks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] They concluded that the system was still immature and that its higher data capacity could increase exposure to attacks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] A 2022 study identified a design flaw in the Evolved Packet System (EPS) that could affect device behavior during network switching.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Growth of the Internet of things increases the number of devices connected through 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] IoT Analytics estimated growth from about 7 billion devices in 2018 to over 21 billion by 2025, raising exposure to DDoS attacks, cryptojacking, and other cyberattacks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Concerns about espionage and data access have influenced national policies.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The United States, Australia, and the United Kingdom have restricted or banned Chinese-made equipment.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] A 2012 report by the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence concluded that equipment from Huawei and ZTE could pose national-security risks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Later assessments by U.S. intelligence agencies warned that Huawei products could allow covert data access.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2022, the FBI reported that Huawei equipment near U.S. military bases could interfere with nuclear communications.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Huawei and the Chinese government deny the allegations.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Analysts note that China's National Security Law could require companies to provide data to authorities if requested.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2020, the United States Department of State launched The Clean Network initiative to promote data privacy and security among allied nations.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] By year-end, more than 60 countries and 200 telecommunications companies had joined, including most NATO, EU, and OECD members.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Some 5G bands, such as n258 at 26 GHz, are close to frequencies used for passive remote sensing by weather and Earth observation satellites, including water vapor measurements at 23.8 GHz.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Interference with satellite observations could reduce the accuracy of numerical weather prediction models and affect sectors such as commercial aviation.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Navy warned that out-of-band emissions from 5G transmissions near 24 GHz could degrade forecasts by up to 30 %.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The 2019 World Radiocommunication Conference set an interim limit of −33 dBW until 2027, followed by −39 dBW.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) and European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) warned that these limits could reduce forecast reliability.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2021–2022, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) warned that some 5G signals could interfere with aircraft radar altimeters, which operate at 4.2–4.4 GHz, while new 5G services use 3.7–4.0 GHz.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Europe uses lower frequencies (3.4–3.8 GHz), reducing the risk.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Some 5G allocations overlap with frequencies used by C band satellite communication systems.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Interference can occur when networks operate in 3.3–3.6 GHz, near satellite reception at 3.4–4.2 GHz Mitigation uses low-noise block downconverters and waveguide filters.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] 5G and Wi-Fi 6E share the 6 GHz band, which enables efficient spectrum use but requires coordination to prevent interference.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Both operate under unlicensed conditions in the US and EU, supporting NR-U and Wi-Fi 6E technologies.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Analysts note that marketing of 5G has often overstated its capabilities.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Common concerns include limited user benefits, short range of mmWave signals, and rebranding of non-5G improvements as 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] A 2020 survey by McKinsey & Company found that operators identified few immediately profitable use cases.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Consumer surveys show mixed attitudes, with skepticism about marketing claims and uneven coverage in early deployments.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Industry groups and network operators state that 5G enables faster speeds and lower latency, though results depend on infrastructure rollout and available spectrum.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In contrast to the initial excitement about the prospects, many firms striving for deployment have encountered reality, users are not eager to upgrade the technology.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Five years after its launch, a majority of users have yet to transition to the new standard.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Public concern about the effects of wireless signals predates 5G technology.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Similar concerns were raised about earlier mobile standards in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), "exposure to intense, direct amounts of non-ionizing radiation may result in tissue damage due to heat.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Some critics argue that existing exposure limits are too lenient or influenced by industry lobbying.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Claims that the use of 5G mobile networks can cause cancer are unsupported by scientific evidence.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Several books making unverified claims about wireless health effects have been published.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] One, by Joseph Mercola, alleged links to ADHD, heart disease, and brain cancer.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Mercola was criticized for promoting misinformation during the COVID-19 pandemic and warned by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for selling unapproved COVID-19 cures.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] According to *The New York Times*, controversy regarding 5G health effects partly originated from an unpublished 2000 report by physicist Bill P.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Curry for the Broward County School Board, which incorrectly concluded that higher-frequency microwaves are absorbed more deeply by the brain.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Later analyses showed that this was a misunderstanding of *in vitro* research results.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Experts noted that millimeter-wave frequencies used by 5G cannot penetrate the skin or reach internal organs.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In a 2019 article, the same newspaper reported that RT America promoted claims linking 5G to diseases such as brain cancer, infertility, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The network aired several such programs in 2019, later cited by numerous blogs and websites.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2019, cities such as Brussels and Geneva temporarily halted 5G rollouts pending radiation assessments.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The Swiss Telecommunications Association stated that studies had not demonstrated adverse health effects from 5G exposure.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Similar debates occurred in the Netherlands, the United States, and the United Kingdom, where some municipalities briefly delayed deployments or issued precautionary statements.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The Food and Drug Administration maintains that existing exposure limits for cellphone radiofrequency energy are sufficient to protect public health.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Low-level electromagnetic fields (EMF) can have measurable biological effects in plants and animals, but research remains inconclusive about health risks to humans.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] A 2019 meta-analysis found that while many *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies detected biological responses to radiofrequency exposure, the evidence did not establish health risks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The rollout of 5G technology began during the COVID-19 pandemic, prompting conspiracy theories that linked 5G to the pandemic.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] These claims led to arson attacks on telecom masts in parts of Europe, including the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and Italy.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In the United Kingdom, at least 61 mobile masts were reportedly set on fire.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] During the early months of the pandemic, Australian anti-lockdown protesters carried anti-5G signs, later connected to broader conspiracy groups.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The second claims that 5G causes COVID-19.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Some versions claim the pandemic hid illnesses blamed on 5G, while others suggest COVID-19 began in Wuhan, one of the first cities with early 5G rollout.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] The marketing of pre-5G technologies refers to the promotion of enhanced 4G networks as precursors or alternatives to 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] Before and during early 5G deployment, some mobile network operators used terms such as "pre-5G", "5G-ready", "4.5G", and "5G Evolution" for upgraded LTE Advanced or LTE Advanced Pro networks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] These networks could use features such as carrier aggregation, 256-QAM, and 4×4 MIMO to increase data rates, but they did not use 5G NR, the radio access technology standardized for 5G networks.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] A notable example was 5G Evolution, introduced by AT&T in 2017 to market higher-speed LTE service.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] AT&T described the service as "a foundation for our evolution to 5G while the 5G standards are being finalized", but technology publications criticized the branding as misleading because the underlying network remained based on LTE technologies rather than 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2019, Sprint sued AT&T, alleging that the 5G Evolution and "5GE" branding misled consumers into believing that they were receiving 5G service.
[src:telecom-5g/5g] In 2020, the National Advertising Review Board recommended that AT&T stop using "5G Evolution" and related claims in advertising, finding that the terms were misleading; AT&T said it disagreed with the decision but would comply with the self-regulatory process.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Compared to lower bands, radio waves in this band have high atmospheric attenuation: they are absorbed by the gases in the atmosphere.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Absorption increases with frequency until at the top end of the band the waves are attenuated to zero within a few meters.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Absorption by humidity in the atmosphere is significant except in desert environments, and attenuation by rain (rain fade) is a serious problem even over short distances.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] However the short propagation range allows smaller frequency reuse distances than lower frequencies.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The short wavelength allows modest size antennas to have a small beam width, further increasing frequency reuse potential.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter waves are used for military fire-control radar, airport security scanners, short range wireless networks, and scientific research.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] In a major new application of millimeter waves, certain frequency ranges near the bottom of the band are being used in the newest generation of cell phone networks, 5G networks.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The design of millimeter-wave circuit and subsystems (such as antennas, power amplifiers, mixers and oscillators) also presents severe challenges to engineers due to semiconductor and process limitations, model limitations and poor *Q* factors of passive devices.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter waves propagate solely by line-of-sight paths.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] They are not refracted by the ionosphere nor do they travel along the Earth as ground waves as lower frequency radio waves do.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] At typical power densities they are blocked by building walls and suffer significant attenuation passing through foliage.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Absorption by atmospheric gases is a significant factor throughout the band and increases with frequency.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] However, this absorption is maximum at a few specific absorption lines, mainly those of oxygen at 60 GHz and water vapor at 24 GHz and 184 GHz.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] At frequencies in the "windows" between these absorption peaks, millimeter waves have much less atmospheric attenuation and greater range, so many applications use these frequencies.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter wavelengths are the same order of size as raindrops, so precipitation causes additional attenuation due to scattering (rain fade) as well as absorption.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The high free space loss and atmospheric absorption limit useful propagation to a few kilometers.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Thus, they are useful for densely packed communications networks such as personal area networks that improve spectrum utilization through frequency reuse.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter waves show "optical" propagation characteristics and can be reflected and focused by small metal surfaces and dielectric lenses around 5 to 30 cm (2 inches to 1 foot) diameter.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Because their wavelengths are often much smaller than the equipment that manipulates them, the techniques of geometric optics can be used.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Diffraction is less than at lower frequencies, although millimeter waves can be diffracted by building edges.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] At millimeter wavelengths, surfaces appear rougher so diffuse reflection increases.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Multipath propagation, particularly reflection from indoor walls and surfaces, causes serious fading.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Doppler shift of frequency can be significant even at pedestrian speeds.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] In portable devices, shadowing due to the human body is a problem.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Since the waves penetrate clothing and their small wavelength allows them to reflect from small metal objects they are used in millimeter wave scanners for airport security scanning.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] This band is commonly used in radio astronomy and remote sensing.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Ground-based radio astronomy is limited to high altitude sites such as Kitt Peak and Atacama Large Millimeter Array (ALMA) due to atmospheric absorption issues.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Satellite-based remote sensing near 60 GHz can determine temperature in the upper atmosphere by measuring radiation emitted from oxygen molecules that is a function of temperature and pressure.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The International Telecommunication Union non-exclusive passive frequency allocation at 57–59.3 GHz is used for atmospheric monitoring in meteorological and climate sensing applications and is important for these purposes due to the properties of oxygen absorption and emission in Earth's atmosphere.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Currently operational U.S. satellite sensors such as the Advanced Microwave Sounding Unit (AMSU) on one NASA satellite (Aqua) and four NOAA (15–18) satellites and the special sensor microwave/imager (SSMI/S) on Department of Defense satellite F-16 make use of this frequency range.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] In the United States, the band 36.0–40.0 GHz is used for licensed high-speed microwave data links, and the 60 GHz band can be used for unlicensed short range (1.7 km) data links with data throughputs up to 2.5 Gbit/s.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The 71–76, 81–86 and 92–95 GHz bands are also used for point-to-point high-bandwidth communication links.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] These higher frequencies do not suffer from oxygen absorption, but require a transmitting license in the US from the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] There are plans for 10 Gbit/s links using these frequencies as well.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] In the case of the 92–95 GHz band, a small 100 MHz range has been reserved for space-borne radios, limiting this reserved range to a transmission rate of under a few gigabits per second.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The band is essentially undeveloped and available for use in a broad range of new products and services, including high-speed, point-to-point wireless local area networks and broadband Internet access.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] WirelessHD is another recent technology that operates near the 60 GHz range.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Highly directional, "pencil-beam" signal characteristics permit different systems to operate close to one another without causing interference.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Potential applications include radar systems with very high resolution.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The Wi-Fi standards IEEE 802.11ad and IEEE 802.11ay operate in the 60 GHz (V band) spectrum to achieve data transfer rates as high as 7 Gbit/s and at least 20 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Uses of the millimeter wave bands include point-to-point communications, intersatellite links, and point-to-multipoint communications.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] In 2013 it was speculated that there were plans to use millimeter waves in future 5G mobile phones.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] In addition, use of millimeter wave bands for vehicular communication is also emerging as an attractive solution to support (semi-)autonomous vehicular communications.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Shorter wavelengths in this band permit the use of smaller antennas to achieve the same high directivity and high gain as larger ones in lower bands.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The immediate consequence of this high directivity, coupled with the high free space loss at these frequencies, is the possibility of a more efficient use of frequencies for point-to-multipoint applications.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Since a greater number of highly directive antennas can be placed in a given area, the net result is greater frequency reuse, and higher density of users.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The high usable channel capacity in this band might allow it to serve some applications that would otherwise use fiber-optic communication or very short links such as for the interconnect of circuit boards.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter wave radar is used in short-range fire-control radar in tanks and aircraft, and automated guns (CIWS) on naval ships to shoot down incoming missiles.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The small wavelength of millimeter waves allows them to track the stream of outgoing bullets as well as the target, allowing the computer fire control system to change the aim to bring them together.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Air Force has developed a nonlethal antipersonnel weapon system called Active Denial System (ADS) which emits a beam of millimeter radio waves with a wavelength of 3 mm (frequency of 95 GHz).
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The weapon causes a person in the beam to feel an intense burning pain, as if their skin is going to catch fire.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The military version had an output power of 100 kilowatts (kW), and a smaller law enforcement version, called Silent Guardian that was developed by Raytheon later, had an output power of 30 kW.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Clothing and other organic materials are transparent to millimeter waves of certain frequencies, so a recent application has been scanners to detect weapons and other dangerous objects carried under clothing, for applications such as airport security.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Privacy advocates are concerned about the use of this technology because, in some cases, it allows screeners to see airport passengers as if without clothing.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The TSA has deployed millimeter wave scanners to many major airports.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Prior to a software upgrade the technology did not mask any part of the bodies of the people who were being scanned.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] However, passengers' faces were deliberately masked by the system.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The photos were screened by technicians in a closed room, then deleted immediately upon search completion.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] "We're getting closer and closer to a required strip-search to board an airplane," said Barry Steinhardt of the American Civil Liberties Union.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] To address this issue, upgrades have eliminated the need for an officer in a separate viewing area.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The new software generates a generic image of a human.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] There is no anatomical differentiation between male and female on the image, and if an object is detected, the software only presents a yellow box in the area.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] If the device does not detect anything of interest, no image is presented.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Passengers can decline scanning and be screened via a metal detector and patted down.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Recent studies at the University of Leuven have proven that millimeter waves can also be used as a non-nuclear thickness gauge in various industries.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter waves provide a clean and contact-free way of detecting variations in thickness.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Practical applications for the technology focus on plastics extrusion, paper manufacturing, glass production and mineral wool production.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Low intensity (usually 10 mW/cm2 or less) electromagnetic radiation of extremely high frequency may be used in human medicine for the treatment of diseases.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] For example, "A brief, low-intensity MMW exposure can change cell growth and proliferation rates, activity of enzymes, state of cell genetic apparatus, function of excitable membranes and peripheral receptors." This treatment is particularly associated with the range of 40–70 GHz.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] This type of treatment may be called *millimeter wave therapy* or *extremely high frequency therapy*.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] This treatment is associated with eastern European nations (e.g., former USSR nations).
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] The Russian Journal *Millimeter waves in biology and medicine* studies the scientific basis and clinical applications of millimeter wave therapy.
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Traffic police use speed-detecting radar guns in the Ka-band (33.4–36.0 GHz).
[src:telecom-5g/millimeter-wave] Millimeter-length electromagnetic waves were first investigated by Jagadish Chandra Bose, who generated waves of frequency up to 60 GHz during experiments in 1894–1896.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO uses the spatial diversity to increase link capacity.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The technology requires multiple antennas at both the transmitter and receiver, along with associated signal processing, to deliver data rate speedups roughly proportional to the number of antennas at each end.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO starts with a high-rate data stream, which is de-multiplexed into multiple, lower-rate streams.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Each of these streams is then modulated and transmitted in parallel with different coding from the transmit antennas, with all streams in the same frequency channel.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] These co-channel, mutually interfering streams arrive at the receiver's antenna array, each having a different spatial signature—gain phase pattern at the receiver’s antennas.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] These distinct array signatures allow the receiver to separate these co-channel streams, demodulate them, and re-multiplex them to reconstruct the original high-rate data stream.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This process is sometimes referred to as *spatial multiplexing*.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The key to MIMO is the sufficient differences in the spatial signatures of the different streams to enable their separation.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This is achieved through a combination of angle spread of the multipaths and sufficient spacing between antenna elements.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In environments with a rich multipath and high angle spread, common in cellular and Wi-Fi deployments, an antenna element spacing at each end of just a few wavelengths can suffice.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] However, in the absence of significant multipath spread, larger element spacing (wider angle separation) is required at either the transmit array, the receive array, or at both.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO is often traced back to 1970s research papers concerning multi-channel digital transmission systems and interference (crosstalk) between wire pairs in a cable bundle: AR Kaye and DA George (1970), Branderburg and Wyner (1974), and W. van Etten (1975, 1976).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Although these are not examples of exploiting multipath propagation to send multiple information streams, some of the mathematical techniques for dealing with mutual interference proved useful to MIMO development.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In the mid-1980s, Jack Salz at Bell Laboratories took this research a step further, investigating multi-user systems operating over "mutually cross-coupled linear networks with additive noise sources" such as time-division multiplexing and dually-polarized radio systems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Methods were developed to improve the performance of cellular radio networks and enable more aggressive frequency reuse in the early 1990s.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Space-division multiple access (SDMA) uses directional or smart antennas to communicate on the same frequency with users in different locations within range of the same base station.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] An SDMA system was proposed by Richard Roy and Björn Ottersten, researchers at ArrayComm, in 1991.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In December 1991, while working on a DARPA project involving signal separation algorithms at Stanford University, Arogyaswami Paulraj discovered that signals from two phones held in one hand could be separated using a three-element receive antenna array in a rich multipath environment.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This discovery led to the foundational patent on MIMO, filed in February 1992 with Professor Thomas Kailath as a co-inventor.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The patent proposed a method for increasing data rates on MIMO links in proportion to the number of antennas used.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] While Paulraj’s patent initially emphasized applications in broadcast TV, which he believed would be an early adopter of the technology, it also proposed broader uses for MIMO in cellular communications.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Paulraj joined the Stanford faculty in 1993, where he built a research group on MIMO.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Later in 1998 and 2004, he founded two startups (Iospan Wireless and Beceem Communications) to commercialize MIMO for mobile networks.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Paulraj has received many recognitions for his work.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] These include the Royal Academy of Engineering (RAE) Prince Philip Medal, the Institution of Engineering and Technology (IET) Faraday Medal, the IEEE Alexander G.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Bell Medal, the Marconi Prize, and induction into the U.S.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Patent and Trademark Office's National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Foschini and Michael Gans of Bell Labs wrote influential papers on MIMO wireless capacity and proposed the BLAST (Bell Labs Layered Space-Time) scheme to layer MIMO data streams and maximize channel capacity.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Foschini received the IEEE Alexander Graham Bell Medal.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Many other key publications followed, significantly advancing the field: G.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Telatar established the fundamental capacity limits of MIMO channels.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Alamouti developed a simple but effective transmit diversity scheme that has been widely adopted.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Calderbank et al. made crucial contributions to the development of space-time codes.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Sampath et al. described the first MIMO-OFDM cellular system developed by Iospan Wireless.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Heath advanced the areas of limited feedback and multi-user MIMO systems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] A torrent of research has followed, and as of 2024, there are over 450,000 research publications on MIMO technology and more than 570,000 global patent publications referencing MIMO or its related techniques.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Iospan Wireless began in late 1998 to develop a MIMO-OFDM physical-layer-based cellular system.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Iospan’s product (Airburst) consisted of a core network, base stations, and CPE terminals.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Airburst did not initially support mobile handovers.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The system was trialed in Santa Clara during 2000-2002 and underwent a customer trial in Dubai in 2002.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Following the 2001 collapse of the Dot-Com bubble, Iospan could not raise additional venture funding and was acquired by Intel in 2003.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Intel integrated Iospan’s MIMO-OFDM technology into the WiMAX broadband mobile standard, IEEE 802.16e standard in 2004.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In the early 2000s, several semiconductor companies also entered the MIMO-OFDM-based WiMAX technology market.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] They included Sequans, Samsung, Intel, Alvarion, and Beceem Communications, which developed modem semiconductors for WiMAX phones.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Beceem gained 65% share of the global market and was acquired by Broadcom Corp.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) standards body adopted MIMO for HSPA+ (Release 7) in 20XX and MIMO-OFDM-based 4G Long Term Evolution (LTE) (Release 8) in 2008.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO-OFDM has since remained the core technology since 2008 for mobile networks, including 5G NR.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In the early 2000s, several companies—Atheros, Cisco, Broadcom, Intel, and Airgo Networks—entered the MIMO‑OFDM Wi‑Fi semiconductor market.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Due to competing proposals within the IEEE 802.11, the first MIMO‑OFDM Wi‑Fi standard (802.11n) was not finalized until 2009.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Several pre-standard products were developed, but the market grew only after the 802.11n standard was ratified.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Airgo Networks was acquired by Qualcomm in December 2006, and Atheros was also acquired by Qualcomm in May 2011.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Sequans did an IPO in 2011 and Alviron filed for bankruptcy in 2013.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Wi-Fi 6 added native support for MU-MIMO.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Currently, 4G/5G and Wi-Fi powered by MIMO enable approximately 70% of internet-based services, accounting for 10% of global GDP.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The GSMA industry alliance estimated the global economic value of mobile networks at $5.7 trillion, and the WiFi alliance estimated the corresponding value for WiFi networks at $3.5 trillion in 2023.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO can be sub-divided into three main categories: precoding, spatial multiplexing (SM), and diversity coding.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Multi-antenna MIMO (or single-user MIMO) technology has been developed and implemented in some standards, e.g., 802.11n products.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Third generation (3G) (CDMA and UMTS) allows for implementing space-time transmit diversity schemes, in combination with transmit beamforming at base stations.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Fourth generation (4G) LTE and LTE Advanced define very advanced air interfaces extensively relying on MIMO techniques.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] LTE primarily focuses on single-link MIMO relying on spatial multiplexing and space-time coding, while LTE-Advanced further extends the design to multi-user MIMO.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In wireless local area networks (WLAN), the IEEE 802.11n (Wi-Fi), MIMO technology is implemented in the standard using three different techniques: antenna selection, space-time coding and possibly beamforming.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The IEEE 802.16e standard incorporates MIMO-OFDMA.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The IEEE 802.11n standard, released in October 2009, recommends MIMO-OFDM.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO is used in mobile radio telephone standards such as 3GPP and 3GPP2.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In 3GPP, High-Speed Packet Access plus (HSPA+) and Long Term Evolution (LTE) standards take MIMO into account.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Moreover, to fully support cellular environments, MIMO research consortia, including IST-MASCOT, propose to develop advanced MIMO techniques, e.g., multi-user MIMO (MU-MIMO).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO wireless communications architectures and processing techniques can be applied to sensing problems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This is studied in a sub-discipline called MIMO radar.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO technology can be used in non-wireless communications systems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] One example is the home networking standard ITU-T G.9963, which defines a powerline communications system that uses MIMO techniques to transmit multiple signals over multiple AC wires (phase, neutral and ground).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In MIMO systems, a transmitter sends multiple streams by multiple transmit antennas.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The transmit streams go through a matrix channel which consists of all $N_{t}N_{r}$ paths between the $N_{t}$ transmit antennas at the transmitter and $N_{r}$ receive antennas at the receiver.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Then, the receiver gets the received signal vectors by the multiple receive antennas and decodes the received signal vectors into the original information.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $\mathbf {y}$ and $\mathbf {x}$ are the receive and transmit vectors, respectively, and $\mathbf {H}$ and $\mathbf {n}$ are the channel matrix and the noise vector, respectively.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $()^{H}$ denotes Hermitian transpose and $\rho$ is the ratio between transmit power and noise power (i.e., transmit SNR).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The spatial correlation of the channel has a strong impact on the ergodic channel capacity with statistical information.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Depending on the statistical properties of the channel, the ergodic capacity is no greater than $\min(N_{t},N_{r})$ times larger than that of a SISO system.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The MIMO system can be described by: $\mathbf {y} =\mathbf {H} \mathbf {x} +\mathbf {n}$ , where $\mathbf {y}$ is the received vector, $\mathbf {H}$ is the channel matrix, $\mathbf {x}$ is the transmitted vector, and $\mathbf {n}$ is the noise vector.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The goal of MIMO detection is to estimate $\mathbf {x}$ from $\mathbf {y}$ given knowledge of $\mathbf {H}$ .This can be posed as a statistical detection problem, and addressed using a variety of techniques including zero-forcing, successive interference cancellation a.k.a.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] V-blast, maximum likelihood estimation and recently, neural network MIMO detection.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Such techniques commonly assume that the channel matrix $\mathbf {H}$ is known at the receiver.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In practice, in communication systems, the transmitter sends a pilot signal and the receiver learns the state of the channel (i.e., $\mathbf {H}$ ) from the received signal Y and the pilot signal X .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Recently, there are works on MIMO detection using deep learning tools which have shown to work better than other methods such as zero-forcing.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The zero forcing (ZF) detector simply solves for the unknown transmitted signals regardless of the noise.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Despite its simplicity, this approach suffers from noise enhancement.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] After decoupling by Equation, the ZF solution ${\hat {x}}_{ZF}$ is either quantized and demapped to binary bits or used to compute the LLR.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Note that such an approximation introduces negligible error rate degradation and significantly reduces the computation needed.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $g_{p}$ denotes the p th column vector of matrix $G_{ZF}^{T}$ , ${\hat {X}}_{ZF}^{(p)}$ is the p th element of the symbol vector ${\hat {x}}_{ZF}$ , and $\chi _{b,j}$ indicates the subset of constellation points whose j th bit has value b .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The minimum mean squared error (MMSE) algorithm detects the transmitted signals, ${\tilde {\mathbf {x} }}$ , through minimizing the mean squared error (MSE), $\mathbb {E} \{({\tilde {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {x} )({\tilde {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {x} )^{H}\}$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $\sigma _{x}^{2}$ and $\sigma _{v}^{2}$ are the signal energy and the noise variance, respectively.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $\mathbf {H} _{(-p)}$ represents the matrix $\mathbf {H}$ with the p th column removed, and $\mathbf {h} _{p}$ is the p th column vector of $\mathbf {H}$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Equation (1.1) is referred to as the biased MMSE detector because the detected signal power is smaller than the transmitted signal power by a factor of $\alpha ^{(p)}/(\alpha ^{(p)}+1)$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $\mathbf {B}$ is a diagonal matrix with the p th diagonal element equal to $(\alpha ^{(p)}+1)/\alpha ^{(p)}$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The unbiased MMSE detection solution has better BER performance than the biased MMSE detection solution.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Interestingly, this phenomenon implies that minimizing the MSE does not necessarily minimize the BER.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Both the ZF and the MMSE detectors are linear.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] There also exist nonlinear methods that solve the MIMO detection problem for spatially multiplexed MIMO systems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Among these nonlinear algorithms, the OSIC is the simplest one.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $Q(\cdot )$ denotes the quantizer and $\mathbf {g} _{p(i)}$ is the column vector of $\mathbf {G} ^{(i)T}$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Note that OSIC is known to perform better than linear detectors at high SNR, but it is worse at low SNR.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Therefore, adequately switching between linear detection and OSIC can further improve the error rate performance.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Although ML provides optimal performance, its complexity grows exponentially with the number of transmit antennas and modulation order, making it impractical for large MIMO systems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] where $\chi ^{P}$ is the P -fold Cartesian product over constellation set $\chi$ , and $M(\mathbf {x} )$ is the metric value of a symbol vector.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The ML detector must search all possible combinations of P symbols, thus the complexity grows exponentially with P .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In light of this huge complexity, the **sphere decoder** (SD) was proposed to reduce the search space in an ML MIMO detector.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The SD only searches those constellation points lying within a P -dimensional hypersphere.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Let the $(i,j)$ th element in $\mathbf {R}$ be $R_{i,j}$ and the p th element in ${\tilde {\mathbf {z} }}$ be ${\tilde {Z}}(p)$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The resulting sphere decoding process becomes a P -level tree search.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In level L , only child nodes from parent nodes satisfying: $\sum _{p=L+1}^{P-1}T(p)<d^{2}$ are considered.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Once the accumulated partial distance: $T(L)+\sum _{p=L+1}^{P-1}T(p)$ exceeds $d^{2}$ , all nodes in the subtree rooted at that child node are removed from the search space.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] is the path with the minimum metric value.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Then, for surviving $X(P-1)$ nodes, the SD procedure proceeds to examine all the underlying $X(P-2)$ and again discards those partial vectors $[X(P-1),X(P-2)]$ for which: $T(P-1)+T(P-2)>d^{2}$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Since $T(p)>0$ , the accumulated PDs increase monotonically, and more nodes are pruned at lower layers.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] With careful design of the radius and search strategy, sphere decoding can approach ML performance with significantly lower average complexity.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Different tree search algorithms significantly affect the sphere decoder's efficiency.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In algorithm design, tree search strategies are commonly categorized into three major types: **depth-first search, breadth-first search,** and **best-first search**.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] As its name implies, this algorithm explores the tree by diving down to the bottommost layer first — called the forward step — until a leaf node is reached or the accumulated partial distance (PD) exceeds the radius constraint.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] When the forward step cannot proceed, a backward step returns the search to the upper layer, and the algorithm continues down another branch.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This process repeats until all nodes satisfying the radius constraint are visited.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In the natural span scheme, the next node is selected randomly.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Its advantage is that it avoids enumerating all possible child nodes, which is a major source of complexity in the closest-point-first scheme.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In the closest-point-first method, the next node is chosen based on the smallest PD.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] When this method is combined with depth-first search, the first full symbol vector found is known as the Babai point.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The radius constraint $d^{2}$ of the sphere decoder can then be updated to the metric value of the Babai point, effectively shrinking the search space.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] If another full leaf node is later discovered with an even smaller metric, the radius can again be updated, reducing the search space further.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Depth-first tree search is favored for its speed.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The first valid full solution (the Babai point) can be found by visiting only P nodes.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] When combined with radius update, the ML solution is often identified quickly.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Thus, this approach is especially suitable for hard-output MIMO detectors.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] However, its drawbacks include variable latency and runtime complexity**.** In some cases, especially under low SNR, the algorithm may need to explore many nodes before finding the ML solution, particularly when it is far from the Babai point.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] To address this, the run-time constraint concept is introduced: a fixed upper limit is imposed on the number of visited nodes.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Once the limit is reached, the search terminates early.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In summary, the depth-first tree search method is best suited for hard-output MIMO detection in high-SNR environments due to its speed and efficiency, especially when combined with radius update strategies.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The breadth-first tree search algorithm features two main properties: (1) multiple nodes are visited simultaneously within a layer, and (2) only forward traversal is allowed (no backward step).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] As a result, all symbol vectors that satisfy the radius constraint are found concurrently once the search reaches the bottommost layer.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Unlike depth-first search, the sphere radius cannot be dynamically updated in breadth-first search.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The initial radius is the sole parameter to balance between complexity and performance.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] If the radius is too small, no valid solution may be found, and the search must be restarted with a larger radius.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Conversely, if the radius is too large, the search may visit too many unnecessary nodes and their descendants.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] A notable issue with this algorithm is the variable number of visited nodes per layer, which poses implementation challenges, especially in hardware design that must accommodate the worst-case scenario.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] A well-known derivative of the breadth-first search is the K-best tree search.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Here, K represents the number of nodes retained at each layer for further downward traversal.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Therefore, the **search complexity is fixed**, determined by K and the number of tree layers.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Several strategies exist to enumerate the best K nodes at a given layer.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Enumerate the best child node of each surviving parent node.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Among these children, determine the overall best node.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] From the parent whose best child was selected, enumerate its second-best child.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Repeat the selection and enumeration process until the top K nodes are determined.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This procedure continues layer by layer.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] A visualization of the K-best tree search is often represented.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In a typical K-best Sphere Decoder (SD), the radius is implicitly set to infinity.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] However, it is possible to combine a fixed radius constraint with the K-best criterion: among nodes with PD below the radius, only K may be selected.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] If the radius is small, fewer than K nodes might be available in a layer, making K act more like a layer-wise runtime constraint.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The choice of K is critical to achieving a good tradeoff between complexity and detection performance.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] For instance, in a 4×4 MIMO system, the maximum affordable number of visited nodes may be around 100; thus, $K\approx 25$ .
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] However, in real implementations, K is often smaller.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] For small K , it is possible that the ancestor of the ML solution is pruned, because although the ML path has the smallest total metric, its early PDs may be larger than other nodes at the same layer.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Unlike depth-first and breadth-first tree search algorithms, the best-first tree search does not follow strict layer boundaries.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In this approach, candidate nodes are defined as all nodes that can be visited next, regardless of their depth in the tree.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] At each traversal step, the best candidate node, i.e., the one with the smallest accumulated partial distance (PD), is visited.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] To manage cross-layer candidates, a node pool is maintained to store all viable candidate nodes and their PDs.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This method achieves the lowest average complexity among ML tree searches.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] However, the best-first tree search has some limitations: 1.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Memory usage: A large node pool is required.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Enumeration overhead: Dynamic control logic is needed to manage the pool.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Soft-output inefficiency**:** Few full-length solutions may be found, which is problematic for soft-output MIMO detection.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The modified best-first (MBF) tree search transforms the M-ary search tree into a binary tree using a first-child/next-sibling structure.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Instead of pushing all M children of a node into the pool, only: - the best child in the next layer, and - the best unvisited sibling are added when a node is visited.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The current node is then removed from the pool.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This encoding reduces the branching factor and keeps the node pool more compact, improving search efficiency while preserving forward and horizontal traversal capabilities.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This technique is similar to standard binary tree encoding in data structures.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The modified best-first with fast descent (MBF-FD) further improves MBF by combining it with depth-first traversal principles.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The idea is to descend quickly along the best child path to reach a leaf node, while pushing best sibling nodes encountered along the way into the pool.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Once a leaf is found, a new search begins from the next best node in the pool.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This method ensures more full-length paths are explored, which is especially beneficial for soft-output MIMO detection requiring multiple high-quality symbol vectors.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] It retains the efficiency of MBF while expanding search diversity and depth.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] MIMO signal testing focuses first on the transmitter/receiver system.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The random phases of the sub-carrier signals can produce instantaneous power levels that cause the amplifier to compress, momentarily causing distortion and ultimately symbol errors.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Signals with a high peak-to-average ratio (PAR) can cause amplifiers to compress unpredictably during transmission.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] OFDM signals are very dynamic, and compression problems can be hard to detect because of their noise-like nature.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Knowing the quality of the signal channel is also critical.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] A channel emulator can simulate how a device performs at the cell edge, can add noise or can simulate what the channel looks like at speed.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] To fully qualify the performance of a receiver, a calibrated transmitter, such as a vector signal generator (VSG), and a channel emulator can be used to test the receiver under a variety of different conditions.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Conversely, the transmitter's performance under a number of different conditions can be verified using a channel emulator and a calibrated receiver, such as a vector signal analyzer (VSA).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Understanding the channel allows for manipulation of the phase and amplitude of each transmitter in order to form a beam.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] To correctly form a beam, the transmitter needs to understand the characteristics of the channel.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This process is called *channel sounding* or channel estimation.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] A known signal is sent to the mobile device that enables it to build a picture of the channel environment.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The mobile device sends back the channel characteristics to the transmitter.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] The transmitter can then apply the correct phase and amplitude adjustments to form a beam directed at the mobile device.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This is called a closed-loop MIMO system.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] For beamforming, it is required to adjust the phases and amplitude of each transmitter.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In a beamformer optimized for spatial diversity or spatial multiplexing, each antenna element simultaneously transmits a weighted combination of two data symbols.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Gans, Foschini and Emre Telatar have shown that the channel capacity (a theoretical upper bound on system throughput) for a MIMO system is increased as the number of antennas is increased, proportional to the smaller of the number of transmit antennas and the number of receive antennas.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] This is known as the multiplexing gain, and this basic finding in information theory is what led to a spurt of research in this area.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Despite the simple propagation models used in the aforementioned seminal works, the multiplexing gain is a fundamental property that can be proved under almost any physical channel propagation model and with practical hardware that is prone to transceiver impairments.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Gore has published an introduction to this area.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] There are many other principal textbooks available as well.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] There exists a fundamental tradeoff between transmit diversity and spatial multiplexing gains in a MIMO system (Zheng and Tse, 2003).
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In particular, achieving high spatial multiplexing gains is of profound importance in modern wireless systems.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] Given the nature of MIMO, it is not limited to wireless communication.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] It can be used for wire line communication as well.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] For example, a new type of DSL technology (gigabit DSL) has been proposed based on binder MIMO channels.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] An important question that attracts the attention of engineers and mathematicians is how to use the multi-output signals at the receiver to recover the multi-input signals at the transmitter.
[src:telecom-5g/mimo] In Shang, Sun and Zhou (2007), sufficient and necessary conditions are established to guarantee the complete recovery of the multi-input signals.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] For this reason, this technology assumes a central role to support 5G mobile networks that are designed to efficiently embrace a plethora of services with very different service level requirements (SLR).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The realization of this service-oriented view of the network leverages on the concepts of software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) that allow the implementation of flexible and scalable network slices on top of a common network infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] From a business model perspective, each network slice is administrated by a mobile virtual network operator (MVNO).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The infrastructure provider (the owner of the telecommunication infrastructure) leases its physical resources to the MVNOs that share the underlying physical network.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] According to the availability of the assigned resources, a MVNO can autonomously deploy multiple network slices that are customized to the various applications provided to its own users.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The history of network slicing can be tracked back to the late 1980s with the introduction of the concept of "slice" in the networking field.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Overlay networks provided the first form of network slicing since heterogeneous network resources were combined to create virtual networks over a common infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] However, they lacked a mechanism that could enable their programmability.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] In the early 2000s, PlanetLab introduced a virtualization framework that allowed groups of users to program network functions in order to obtain isolated and application-specific slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The advent of SDN technologies in 2009 further extended the programmability capabilities via open interfaces that enabled the realization of fully configurable and scalable network slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] In the context of mobile networks, network slicing evolved from the concept of RAN sharing that was initially introduced in the LTE standard.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Examples of such technology are multi-operator radio access networks (MORAN) and multi-operator core networks (MOCN), which allow network operators to share common LTE resources within the same radio access network (RAN).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Network slicing emerges as an essential technique in 5G networks to accommodate such different and possibly contrasting quality of service (QoS) requirements exploiting a single physical network infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The basic idea of network slicing is to "slice" the original network architecture in multiple logical and independent networks that are configured to effectively meet the various services requirements.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] In commercial terms, network slicing allows a mobile operator to create specific virtual networks that cater to particular clients and use cases.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Certain applications - such as mobile broadband, machine-to-machine communications (e.g. in manufacturing or logistics), or smart cars - will benefit from leveraging different aspects of 5G technology.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] One might require higher speeds, another low latency, and yet another access to edge computing resources.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] By creating separate slices that prioritise specific resources a 5G operator can offer tailored solutions to particular industries.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Some sources insist this will revolutionise industries like marketing, augmented reality, or mobile gaming, while others are more cautious, pointing to unevenness in network coverage and poor reach of advantages beyond increased speed.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Slicing will be very useful to MVNOs as different use cases can be supported in a layer based on parameters like low latency high speed for video streaming for OTT focused MVNOs, similarly telemetry operations could have lower speed parameter and as on.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Although there are different proposals of network slice architectures, it is possible to define a general architecture that maps the common elements of each solution into a general and unified framework.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] From a high-level perspective, the network slicing architecture can be considered as composed of two mains blocks, one dedicated to the actual slice implementation and the other dedicated to the slice management and configuration.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The first block is designed as a multi-tier architecture composed by three layers (service layer, network function layer, infrastructure layer), where each one contributes to the slice definition and deployment with distinct tasks.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The second block is designed as a centralized network entity, generically denoted as *network slice controller*, that monitors and manages the functionalities between the three layers in order to efficiently coordinate the coexistence of multiple slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The service layer interfaces directly with the network business entities (e.g.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] MVNOs and 3rd party service providers) that share the underlying physical network and it provides a unified vision of the service requirements.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Each service is formally represented as *service instance*, which embeds all the network characteristics in the form of SLA requirements that are expected to be fully satisfied by a suitable slice creation.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The network function layer is in charge of the creation of each network slice according to service instance requests coming from the upper layer.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] It is composed of a set of *network functions* that embody well-defined behaviors and interfaces.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Multiple network functions are placed over the virtual network infrastructure and chained together to create an end-to-end network slice instance that reflects the network characteristics requested by the service.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The configuration of the network functions are performed by means of a set of *network operations* that allow management of their full lifecycle (from their placement when a slice is created to their de-allocation when the function provided is no longer needed).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] To increase resource usage efficiency, the same network function can be simultaneously shared by different slices at the cost of an increase in the complexity of operations management.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Conversely, a one-to-one mapping between each network function and each slice eases the configuration procedures, but can lead to poor and inefficient resource usage.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The infrastructure layer represents the actual physical network topology (radio access network, transport network and core network) upon which every network slice is multiplexed and it provides the physical network resources to host the several network functions composing each slice.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The network domain of the available resources includes a heterogeneous set of infrastructure components like data centers (storage and computation capacity resources), devices enabling network connectivity such as routers (networking resources) and base stations (radio bandwidth resources).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The network slice controller is defined as a network orchestrator, which interfaces with the various functionalities performed by each layer to coherently manage each slice request.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The benefit of such network element is that it enables an efficient and flexible slice creation that can be reconfigured during its life-cycle.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Due to the complexity of the performed tasks which address different purposes, the network slice controller can be composed by multiple orchestrators that independently manage a subset of functionalities of each layer.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] To fulfill the service requirements, the various orchestration entities need to coordinate with each other by exchanging high-level information about the state of the operations involved in the slice creation and deployment.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Slice isolation is an important requirement that allows enforcing the core concept of network slicing about the simultaneous coexistence of multiple slices sharing the same infrastructure.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] This property is achieved by imposing that each slice's performance must not have any impact on the other slice's performance.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Slicing has become an important part of 5G networks, but it doesn't have to forget to guarantee the QoS.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Some studies have demonstrated that formulating the problem with the QoS as a stochastic problem, permit us to maximize the average throughput of the AP, while satisfying the constraints related to the QoS.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Monetizing 5G services faster is one of the topics that interests network operators the most because the costs of building and maintaining 5G networks are high, and it's difficult to predict the demand for 5G services.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] 5G network slicing is one of the effective ways to offer customized services for different industries such as manufacturing, transportation, and healthcare.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Combined with AIOps, ML/AI-driven automation and 5G lifecycle optimization, it can reduce OpEx and increase revenues for network operators.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] In the 3GPP 5G core architecture, the user plane and control plane functions are separated.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Control plane capabilities, for instance, session management, access authentication, policy management, and user data storage are independent of the user plane functionality.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The user plane handles packet forwarding, encapsulation or de-capsulation, and associated transport level specifics.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] This separation leads to the distribution of the user plane functions close to the edge of network slices (e.g., so as to reduce latency) and to be independent of the control plane.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The AMF (as a function of the CP) controls UEs that have been authenticated to use the services of the operator and manages the mobility of the UEs across the gNBs.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The SMF (again part of the CP) manages the sessions of UEs, while AMF transmits the session management messages between the UEs and SMF.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] UPF (as part of the UP) performs the processing and forwarding of the user data.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] NSSF (as a function of the CP) is responsible for the management and orchestration of network slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] CSMF (as a function of the CP) translates the requirements of services to requirements relating to network slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] 5G Core network functions can be sliced to support specific services for different UEs.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Thanks to the modular nature of the 5G core, the network functions of the 5G core can be split and shared between different network slices to reduce management complexity.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] In general, we can perform 5G core network slicing in two ways.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] We can implement dedicated core network functions per network slice.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] In this architecture, each network slice has a set of completely dedicated core network functions (e.g., AUSF, AMF, SMF, and UDM).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The UEs can access various services from network slices and different core networks.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Alternatively, we can share some control plane functions between the network slices while others such as user plane functions are slice specific (e.g., UPF).
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] AMF is usually shared by several network slices, while SMF and UPF are usually dedicated to specific network slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The AMF function will be shared between different network slices in order to reduce the mobility management signaling when the UE uses the services of different network slices simultaneously.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] For example, UE location management or the control signaling between the UE and the old AMF will be reduced when it will be connected to the new AMF of another network slice.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Also, UDM and NSSF are typically shared by all network slices to reduce the management complexity of network slices.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] The emergence of network slicing also exposes novel security and privacy challenges, primarily related to aspects such as network slicing life-cycle security, inter-slice security, intra-slice security, slice broker security, zero-touch network and management security, and blockchain security.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Therefore, enhancing the security, privacy, and trust of network slicing has become a key research area toward realizing the true capabilities of 5G.
[src:telecom-5g/network-slicing] Various security solutions are proposed for resolving the security threats, challenges, and issues of network slicing.
